        <div class="p-6 flex flex-col flex-1">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2 text-heading-light">How to Prevent Winter Pipe Bursts</h3>
          <div class="text-body-light space-y-3">
            <p>Winter can be harsh on your plumbing system. When temperatures drop, water inside your pipes can freeze, expand, and cause pipes to burst—leading to costly water damage. To prevent this, insulate exposed pipes in unheated areas like basements, attics, and garages. Pipe insulation is affordable and easy to install.</p>
            <p>Let faucets drip slightly during extreme cold to keep water moving and reduce the risk of freezing. Seal any cracks or openings in walls near pipes to keep cold air out. If you plan to be away, keep your home heated to at least 55°F (13°C) and ask a neighbor to check on your property.</p>
            <p>If a pipe does freeze, turn off the main water supply and call a professional plumber immediately. Taking these precautions can save you from major headaches and expensive repairs.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
